<item>
 <title>Making Garden Insect Repellent</title>
 <link>http://www.careforcows.org/news/making_garden_insect_repell</link>
 <description>&lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;&gt;&lt;img width=&quot;151&quot; height=&quot;180&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;bottom&quot; src=&quot;/images/news/repellent/BabaYogiraj.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div align=&quot;left&quot;&gt;Under the direction of Nepali born Yogacarya Dilliraj Ghimire, 37, who is certified by the Go-Vigyana Research Center in Nagpur, Maharastra, Care for Cows has started producing garden insect repellents, air-purifying incense, medicines, and hygienic body ointments including massage oil, tooth powder, and shampoo from the by-products of the cow.  Part of the procedure for making garden insect repellent is boiling cow urine and neem leaves in a copper vessel on a fire fueled with dried cow dung. The concentrate is then diluted and sprayed on insect infested vegetables and plants including Tulasi. This product is very effective in repelling a large variety of insects but does not kill them. A different variety of this solution is effective for ridding the soil of underground insects that feed on the roots of vegetables.&lt;/div&gt;
</description>
